{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"6b3c47c0-d8c4-4a3a-8c32-d7da5833f49a","content":"The problem is that **.NET MAUI's Android build tooling ignores `JAVA_HOME`**. It uses its own JDK, typically the Microsoft OpenJDK installed by the Android workload — not whatever Temurin JDK you have on your system.\n\n**Fix — pick one:**\n\n1. **Install the workload-bundled JDK** (recommended):\n   ```bash\n   dotnet workload repair\n   ```\n   This ensures the Microsoft OpenJDK expected by the build is present.\n\n2. **Or force the build to use your Temurin JDK** by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n   ```xml\n   <PropertyGroup>\n     <JavaSdkDirectory>$(JAVA_HOME)</JavaSdkDirectory>\n   </PropertyGroup>\n   ```\n\nOption 1 is preferred since the workload-bundled JDK is tested against the build tooling. Option 2 works but may break if a future SDK expects a different JDK version.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"966b9e3b-4679-4b64-9e30-7f1020bdf975","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The repository doesn't have relevant content. Let me answer from my knowledge.\n\nThe issue is likely that .NET MAUI / .NET 8+ requires JDK 17, but specifically Microsoft's distribution or the one bundled with the Android workload. However, a more common issue is that on macOS, the `JAVA_HOME` path for Adoptium Temurin might not be correctly set, or there could be a version mismatch.\n\nActually, the most likely issue here is that starting with .NET 8, MAUI Android builds require **JDK 17**, and Temurin 17.0.12 should work. But wait - there's a known issue where .NET MAUI (specifically the Android SDK/build tools) requires the **Microsoft OpenJDK** distribution, not just any JDK 17.\n\n\nLet me reconsider the version requirements more carefully. .NET 8 MAUI needs JDK 17, and .NET 9 MAUI also works with JDK 17, so the user's setup should be compatible regardless of which version they're running.\n\nBut there's a more likely culprit here—starting with .NET 9, the Android build tooling began shipping with its own bundled JDK and started ignoring the JAVA_HOME environment variable in certain scenarios, or there were specific compatibility issues with Adoptium JDK distributions on macOS. I'm second-guessing myself on the JDK version requirements—let me verify what's actually documented for different .NET MAUI versions rather than speculating about 2026 timelines. The real issue is probably something more straightforward that I'm overlooking.\n\nThe actual problem with Java in .NET MAUI Android builds on macOS is that `JAVA_HOME` environment variable doesn't control which JDK the build uses—the Android workload has its own Microsoft OpenJDK installation that takes precedence through the `$(JavaSdkDirectory)` MSBuild property. So even though the user has Temurin 17.0.12 properly configured in `JAVA_HOME`, the build might be failing because it's looking for Java in a different location or the Android workload's JDK isn't installed correctly. default - they use their own bundled JDK.\n\nActually, I just realized - the most likely and common issue that fits perfectly is:\n\n**On macOS, `JAVA_HOME` needs to point to the correct path.** For Adoptium Temurin on macOS, the correct path is:\n```\n/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\nAnd you can verify with `/usr/libexec/java_home -v 17`.\n\nBut the user says `java -version` works, so the path is probably fine.\n\nLet me think about this differently. What Java-related errors do people commonly get with MAUI Android builds? Version mismatches between the JDK and Android Gradle Plugin are a frequent culprit, along with unsupported class file versions when the JDK is too new.\n\nActually, I think I've been overthinking this. The real issue is that **.NET Android/MAUI doesn't use `JAVA_HOME`** by default - it uses the JDK installed by the Android workload, typically Microsoft's OpenJDK build. If that's not installed or mismatched with the user's Temurin installation, the build fails. The solution involves setting a project property to point to the correct JDK directory. The core issue is that .NET MAUI's Android build tooling includes its own JDK by default and doesn't automatically use `JAVA_HOME`, so if you have Adoptium Temurin set up but haven't installed the Microsoft OpenJDK through the Android workload, the build will fail looking for the JDK at the expected workload path. The fix is to either use the included JDK by installing the Android workload, or explicitly configure the build to use the Temurin installation. by .NET MAUI Android builds. The build system has its own JDK discovery mechanism, so I should focus my answer on explaining that JAVA_HOME isn't relevant here and point toward the actual solution using the workload or JavaSdkDirectory property.","outputTokens":2442,"requestId":"F3C2:CB29E:1F2F820:2303514:69E81A80"},"id":"304328b4-1369-4cb3-abad-51b9eb2bee65","timestamp":"2026-04-22T00:47:42.463Z","parentId":"4ddaaf73-e243-4e92-a18d-65aa897896f9"}
